<DOC><DOCNO> AP890211-0071 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-11-89 1105EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Hurricane     02-11 0233</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Hurricane,0242</SECOND><HEAD>Hurricane Harry Hits New Caledonia</HEAD><DATELINE>NOUMEA, New Caledonia (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A hurricane with winds up to 125 mphstruck the north coast of this French Pacific island territorySaturday, causing heavy damage but no injuries or deaths,authorities said.   Roads were closed, electricity, water and telephone service werecut and villages were isolated in the heavy rains dumped on thearchipelego by Hurricane Harry, according to officials in thecapital, Noumea.   A large number of trees were uprooted, police said.   The eye of the hurricane passed over the island about 9 p.m., andthe storm seemed to take a turn toward the east, New Caledonia'sweather service reported.   It blew over Fiji on Friday, killing four people and devastatingseveral hundred acres of sugar cane, according to the Fiji weatherservice.   In Koumac, 250 miles from Noumea and the largest town in northernNew Caledonia, a school was damaged and a hospital was floodedduring the storm.   No precise damage estimate was immediately available.   The airline Air-Caledonia told the French news agency AgenceFrance-Presse it had canceled all flights to and from New Caledonia,a group of islands covering 7,335 square miles northeast ofAustralia.   Residents of New Caledonia were warned to avoid traveling on seaor land and to take measures to protect their homes.   In early January, Hurricane Delilha caused two deaths andconsiderable damage in New Caledonia.</TEXT></DOC>